Meteorological data timeseries analysis with python¶

This is the meteorological data timeseries analysis jupyter notebook sample. It based on Pandas dataframes, numpy, scipy and plotly python libraries. The creator of the notebook: MMath, Egor Zamotaev (e-mail: egor.zamotaev@mail.ru).

Part 1. Basic meteorological data timeseries analysis¶

Download dataset from this link (registration is needed): http://meteo.ru/data/162-temperature-precipitation

Data preparations¶

# Declare functions
def getT():
    return ["TemperatureMin", "Temperature", "TemperatureMax"]
def getP():
    return ["Precipitation"]

# Get data from file
f = open("28698.txt","r")
data = [["Station Idx","Year","Month","Day","Quality","TemperatureMin", "Temperature", "TemperatureMax", "Precipitation"]]
for lines in f:
    rowData = lines.replace("\n","").replace(" ","").split(";")
    lst = []
    for s in rowData:
        d = 0
        try:
            d = float(s)
        except Exception: 
            # OOps
            d
        lst.append(d)
    data.append(lst)  

cols = 9
rows = len(data)

# Transform data to pandas df
headers = data.pop(0) # gives the headers as list and leaves data
df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns = headers)
date = pd.DataFrame(pd.to_datetime(df.Year*10000+df.Month*100+df.Day,format='%Y%m%d'), columns=["Date"])
df = df.drop(["Year","Month","Day"],axis=1)
df.insert(1,"Date",date)
df = df.set_index("Date")
df = df.dropna()

# draw Temperature and Precipitation graphics
layout = go.Layout(
    title="Temperature data daily changes",
    xaxis=dict(title = "Date", type='date'),
    yaxis=dict(title = "Day Temperature, °C"),
)
temperatureTraces = []
temperatureTraces.append(go.Scatter(x = df.index, y=df["TemperatureMin"], name = "Min"))
temperatureTraces.append(go.Scatter(x = df.index, y=df["Temperature"], name = "Ave"))
temperatureTraces.append(go.Scatter(x = df.index, y=df["TemperatureMax"], name = "Max"))
fig = go.Figure(data=temperatureTraces, layout=layout)
py.iplot(fig)

Rolling year-decade mean temperature and precipitation sum¶

In [7]:
data = df[["Temperature"]].resample("Y").mean().rolling(10, min_periods=10).mean().dropna()

# Estimate trend
temperature = data["Temperature"].tolist()
idx = np.arange(0,len(temperature))
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(idx,temperature)
line = slope * idx + intercept

# Draw
layout = go.Layout(
    title="Year-decade mean rolling temperature. Increases by " + str(round(slope,2)) + "°C/Year",
    xaxis=dict(title = "Date", type='date'),
    yaxis=dict(title = "Temperature, °C"),
)
trace1 = go.Scatter(x = data.index, y=data["Temperature"], name="Data")
trace2 = go.Scatter(x = data.index, y=line, name='Trend')
fig = go.Figure(data=[trace1,trace2], layout=layout)
py.iplot(fig)



# The same for hummidity sum
data = df[getP()].resample("Y").sum().rolling(10, min_periods=10).mean().dropna()

# Estimate trend
precipitation = data["Precipitation"].tolist()
idx = np.arange(0,len(precipitation))
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(idx,precipitation)
line = slope * idx + intercept

# Draw
layout = go.Layout(
    title="Year-decade mean rolling precipitation sum. \nIncreases by " + str(round(slope,2)) + "mm/Year",
    xaxis=dict(title = "Date", type='date'),
    yaxis=dict(title = "Precipitation Sum, mm"),
)
trace1 = go.Scatter(x = data.index, y=data["Precipitation"], name="Data")
trace2 = go.Scatter(x = data.index, y=line, name='Trend')
fig = go.Figure(data=[trace1,trace2], layout=layout)
py.iplot(fig)

As we can see on the graphs, there are sufficient trends to increase temperature and precipitation for last 50 years. Unfortinately, we can't understand the nature of this trends, we can only to hypothesize...

Chain increase temp for temperatures¶

In [8]:
data = df[["Temperature"]].resample("M").mean().dropna()
data = (data - data.shift(1)).dropna()

# Draw
layout = go.Layout(
    title="Chain increase temp for temperatures",
    xaxis=dict(title = "Date", type='date'),
    yaxis=dict(title = "Chain increase temp temerature, °C"),
)
trace = go.Scatter(x = data.index, y=data["Temperature"])
fig = go.Figure(data=[trace], layout=layout)
py.iplot(fig)

# Get frequencies
midTemperature = data["Temperature"].tolist()
data = abs(sp.fft(midTemperature))
half = int(len(data)/2)
data = data[:half]
data /= max(data)
frequencies = fftfreq(len(midTemperature)) * 12

# Draw
layout = go.Layout(
    title="Chain increase temp spectre for temperatures",
    xaxis=dict(title = "Frequency (per 1 year)"),
    yaxis=dict(title = "Chain increase temp normalized magnitude"),
)
trace = go.Scatter(x = frequencies, y=data)
fig = go.Figure(data=[trace], layout=layout)
py.iplot(fig)

As we can see there are two main periods: one year and half year. First is the common Earth - Solar movement cycle, and second - it's a question for me... I don't know and may only suppose. So, we can see near 3 and 4 fluctuation/per year subdominant cycles. Maybe it's also connected with cosmic cycle or maybe it connected with Earth hemispheres inner climate, ocean cycles, etc. I need to read more about it.

Days of sustainable temerature transition over the 0°C¶

Algorithm explanation: http://aisori.meteo.ru/AisoriHelp/Part_2.htm

In [10]:
def day0(x):
    periods = []
    i = 0
    n = len(x) - 1
    while i < n:
        
        period = []
        while i < n:
            if x[i] >= 0:
                period.append(x[i])
                i += 1
            else:
                break
        if len(period) > 0:
            periods.append(period)
        
        period = []
        while i < n:
            if x[i] < 0:
                period.append(x[i])
                i += 1
            else:
                break
        if len(period) > 0:
            periods.append(period)
        
    # we have periods, next we can find the next one with positive sum > negative sum
    sums = []
    for i in range(0,len(periods)):
        sums.append(sum(periods[i]))
    
    # search spring day 0 temperature transition
    springDay0 = x.index[0]
    i = 0
    while i < len(sums):
        if(sums[i] < 0):
            i += 1
        else:
            finded = True
            for j in range(i + 1, len(sums)):
                if sums[j] < 0 and abs(sums[j]) > sums[i]:
                    finded = False
            if finded:
                dayIdx = 0
                for j in range(0, i):
                    dayIdx += len(periods[j])
                springDay0 = x.index[dayIdx]
                break
            else:
                i += 1
                
    # the same stuff for autumn
    autumnDay0 = x.index[0]
    while i < len(sums):
        if(sums[i] > 0):
            i += 1
        else:
            finded = True
            for j in range(i + 1, len(sums)):
                if sums[j] > 0 and sums[j] > abs(sums[i]):
                    finded = False
            if finded:
                dayIdx = 0
                for j in range(0, i):
                    dayIdx += len(periods[j])
                autumnDay0 = x.index[dayIdx]
                break
            else:
                i += 1      

    return [springDay0, autumnDay0]

def dateToNthDay(date, format='%Y-%m-%d %h:%m:%s'):
    date = pd.to_datetime(date, format=format)
    new_year_day = pd.Timestamp(year=date.year, month=1, day=1)
    return (date - new_year_day).days + 1

def dayN(x, type = 0):
    return dateToNthDay(x[0][type])

data = df[["Temperature"]].resample("Y")
# data = data.agg([("day0",lambda x: day0(x))])
data = data.apply(day0)
data = data.rename(index=str,columns={"Temperature":"DaysDates"})
data["DaySpring"]=data.apply(lambda x: dayN(x),axis = 1)
data["DayAutumn"]=data.apply(lambda x: dayN(x, 1),axis = 1)
data["DayDiff"]=data["DayAutumn"] - data["DaySpring"]
# data.index = [s[0:4] for s in data.index.tolist()]
data = data.drop(columns=["DaysDates"],axis=1)
data = data.rolling(10, min_periods=10).mean().dropna()
data

Part 2. Statistical analysis of meteorological dataset¶

Descriptive statistics¶

In [11]:
def describe(df, stats = ["var", "skew", "kurt", "mad"]):
    d = df.describe()
    d = d.append(df.reindex(axis=1).agg(stats))
    s = d.loc["max",:] - d.loc["min",:]
    s.name = "R"
    d = d.append(s)
    s = d.loc["R",:]/d.loc["mean",:]
    s.name = "R/mean"
    d=d.append(s)
    d = d.drop(["25%","50%", "75%"],axis=0)
    return d
In [12]:
def describeAllset(df):
    data = df[["Temperature"] + getP()]
    data["Temperature Temp"] = data["Temperature"] - data["Temperature"].shift(1)
    data = data.dropna()[["Temperature","Temperature Temp", "Precipitation"]]
    d = describe(data)
#     d.loc["R/mean","Temperature Temp"]=""

    precipitationMonth = data["Precipitation"].resample("M")
    precipitationMonthSum = precipitationMonth.sum()
    precipitationMonthSum.name = "PrecipitationSumMonth"
    precipitationData = pd.DataFrame(precipitationMonthSum)
    def precipitation0Day(x):
        maxDays = 0
        nowDays = 0
        for i in x:
            if i == 0:
                nowDays += 1
                if nowDays > maxDays:
                    maxDays = nowDays
            else:
                nowDays = 0
        return maxDays
    precipitation0Days = precipitationMonth.apply(precipitation0Day)
    precipitationData["Precipitation0Days"]= precipitation0Days
    p = describe(precipitationData)

    result = pd.concat([d,p],axis=1)
    return result

dif = last10.sub(first10)

def orange(val):
    color = 'orange'
    return 'background-color: %s' % color
def blue(val):
    color = 'cyan'
    return 'background-color: %s' % color
dif.style.applymap(orange,subset=pd.IndexSlice["mean","Temperature"])\
         .applymap(orange,subset=pd.IndexSlice["min":"max","Temperature"])\
         .applymap(blue,subset=pd.IndexSlice["mean","PrecipitationSumMonth"])

Empiric probability density functions estimation¶

In [19]:
import warnings
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import scipy.stats as st
import statsmodels as sm
import matplotlib
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

matplotlib.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (16.0, 12.0)
matplotlib.style.use('ggplot')

# Create models from data
def best_fit_distribution(data, bins=200, ax=None):
    """Model data by finding best fit distribution to data"""
    # Get histogram of original data
    y, x = np.histogram(data, bins=bins, density=True)
    x = (x + np.roll(x, -1))[:-1] / 2.0

    # Distributions to check
#     DISTRIBUTIONS = [        
#         st.alpha,st.anglit,st.arcsine,st.beta,st.betaprime,st.bradford,st.burr,st.cauchy,st.chi,st.chi2,st.cosine,
#         st.dgamma,st.dweibull,st.erlang,st.expon,st.exponnorm,st.exponweib,st.exponpow,st.f,st.fatiguelife,st.fisk,
#         st.foldcauchy,st.foldnorm,st.frechet_r,st.frechet_l,st.genlogistic,st.genpareto,st.gennorm,st.genexpon,
#         st.genextreme,st.gausshyper,st.gamma,st.gengamma,st.genhalflogistic,st.gilbrat,st.gompertz,st.gumbel_r,
#         st.gumbel_l,st.halfcauchy,st.halflogistic,st.halfnorm,st.halfgennorm,st.hypsecant,st.invgamma,st.invgauss,
#         st.invweibull,st.johnsonsb,st.johnsonsu,st.ksone,st.kstwobign,st.laplace,st.levy,st.levy_l,st.levy_stable,
#         st.logistic,st.loggamma,st.loglaplace,st.lognorm,st.lomax,st.maxwell,st.mielke,st.nakagami,st.ncx2,st.ncf,
#         st.nct,st.norm,st.pareto,st.pearson3,st.powerlaw,st.powerlognorm,st.powernorm,st.rdist,st.reciprocal,
#         st.rayleigh,st.rice,st.recipinvgauss,st.semicircular,st.t,st.triang,st.truncexpon,st.truncnorm,st.tukeylambda,
#         st.uniform,st.vonmises,st.vonmises_line,st.wald,st.weibull_min,st.weibull_max,st.wrapcauchy
#     ]
    DISTRIBUTIONS = [ 
        st.norm, st.expon, st.uniform, st.johnsonsb, st.laplace, st.rayleigh, st.beta
    ]

    # Best holders
    best_distribution = st.norm
    best_params = (0.0, 1.0)
    best_sse = np.inf

    # Estimate distribution parameters from data
    for distribution in DISTRIBUTIONS:

        # Try to fit the distribution
        try:
            # Ignore warnings from data that can't be fit
            with warnings.catch_warnings():
                warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

                # fit dist to data
                params = distribution.fit(data)

                # Separate parts of parameters
                arg = params[:-2]
                loc = params[-2]
                scale = params[-1]

                # Calculate fitted PDF and error with fit in distribution
                pdf = distribution.pdf(x, loc=loc, scale=scale, *arg)
                sse = np.sum(np.power(y - pdf, 2.0))
                
                # if axis pass in add to plot
                try:
                    if ax:
                        pd.Series(pdf, x).plot(ax=ax)
                    end
                except Exception:
                    pass

                # identify if this distribution is better
                if best_sse > sse > 0:
                    best_distribution = distribution
                    best_params = params
                    best_sse = sse

        except Exception:
            pass

    return (best_distribution.name, best_params)

def make_pdf(dist, params, size=10000):
    """Generate distributions's Probability Distribution Function """

    # Separate parts of parameters
    arg = params[:-2]
    loc = params[-2]
    scale = params[-1]

    # Get sane start and end points of distribution
    start = dist.ppf(0.01, *arg, loc=loc, scale=scale) if arg else dist.ppf(0.01, loc=loc, scale=scale)
    end = dist.ppf(0.99, *arg, loc=loc, scale=scale) if arg else dist.ppf(0.99, loc=loc, scale=scale)

    # Build PDF and turn into pandas Series
    x = np.linspace(start, end, size)
    y = dist.pdf(x, loc=loc, scale=scale, *arg)
    pdf = pd.Series(y, x)

    return pdf

def drawBestFitPDF(data):
    best_fit_name, best_fit_params = best_fit_distribution(data, 20)
    best_dist = getattr(st, best_fit_name)
    print("The nearest distribution type is", best_fit_name)
    
    # Make PDF with best params
    pdf = make_pdf(best_dist, best_fit_params, 200)
            
    # Display
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
    ax = pdf.plot(lw=2, label='PDF', legend=True)
    data.plot(kind='hist', bins=20, density=True, alpha=0.5, label='Data', legend=True, ax=ax)

Part 3. R/S analysis. Hurst exponent interpretation¶

More info at page: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurst_exponent

In [33]:
from hurst import compute_Hc

def calcHurstExponent(df):

    H, c, data = compute_Hc(df)

    # Plot
    f, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.plot(data[0], c*data[0]**H, color="deepskyblue")
    ax.scatter(data[0], data[1], color="purple")
    ax.set_xscale('log')
    ax.set_yscale('log')
    ax.set_xlabel('Time interval')
    ax.set_ylabel('R/S ratio')
    ax.grid(True)
    plt.show()

    print("H={:.4f}, c={:.4f}".format(H,c))
    
    if H > 0.5:
        print("H > 0.5 therefore the process is persistent (memory/trend safe).")
        if H == 1:
            print("Also it is fully preditable.")
    elif H < 0.5:
        print("H < 0.5 therefore the process in antipersistent (stochastic).")
    else:
        print("H = 0.5 the godbless uncertainty!")

The daily temperature is unpredictable.
